<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the `sys_dictionary` row that
    declares the `type` Choice field on the `x_casemgmt_case_task` custom table
    inside the scoped application `x_casemgmt`.

    Per AAP Section 0.5.7 (Data-Model Mapping verbatim) for x_casemgmt_case_task:

        Field   Type     Constraints
        type    Choice   Investigation, Review, Follow-up, Other

    Per AAP Section 0.4.1 (Refactored Structure Planning):
        choices/sys_choice_case_task_type.xml -> Investigation, Review,
        Follow-up, Other

    THIS DICTIONARY ENTRY ONLY DECLARES THAT THE `type` CHOICE FIELD EXISTS
    ON THE PARENT TABLE. The choice values themselves (Investigation, Review,
    Follow-up, Other) are authored as separate sys_choice records in
    ../choices/sys_choice_case_task_type.xml. This separation is a deliberate
    consequence of the ServiceNow Choice-field design pattern: a sys_dictionary
    row declares the column shape; sibling sys_choice rows declare the allowed
    string-label values keyed by `name` + `element` lookup against this entry.
    New task types can later be added by appending sys_choice rows WITHOUT
    altering this dictionary entry.

    OPERATIONAL ROLE OF THE `type` FIELD ON CASE_TASK ROWS:
      - Categorizes the task by activity-class so that internal users can
        triage at-a-glance: an "Investigation" task implies fact-finding
        work; a "Review" task implies a documentation/sign-off step; a
        "Follow-up" task implies a callback or correspondence with a
        requester; and "Other" is the deliberate escape valve for tasks
        that resist neat categorization.
      - Surfaces on the auto-generated x_casemgmt_case_task list view per
        AAP Section 0.4.4 ("Internal user UI" requires "ServiceNow's
        automatic native list and form views for the three custom tables").
      - Surfaces on the auto-generated form layout when a user opens an
        individual task record.
      - Surfaces in the parent case's Related List of tasks (rendered via
        the `case` reference field declared in
        ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_task_case.xml). The Type column
        appears beside Subject so that an internal user reviewing a case
        sees what KIND of work each child task represents without opening
        each task individually.
      - The synthetic seed data per AAP Section 0.7.4 minimum-data
        thresholds (at least one open and one closed task on selected
        demo cases per AAP Section 0.3.1) populates this field across
        the four supported labels to exercise downstream filters and to
        ensure the choice list itself round-trips cleanly through the
        Update Set re-import.
      - The Agent Workspace dashboard's "My overdue tasks" list report
        (AAP Section 0.5.1: list filtered by
        `due_date < javascript:gs.daysAgoStart(0) AND status != Closed AND
        assigned_to = javascript:gs.getUserID()`) does NOT aggregate by
        this field in the POC; type is purely a categorical descriptor
        on the task row, not a discriminator for any flow trigger or
        report grouping. This is INTENTIONALLY different from
        x_casemgmt_case.type, which IS the discriminator that selects
        which Flow Designer state-machine flow handles a case
        (general_inquiry_state_machine.xml vs complaint_state_machine.xml
        per AAP Section 0.5.5). x_casemgmt_case_task has only ONE
        task-status workflow shared across all task types, so
        case_task.type does not need to be a flow-routing discriminator.

    Semantic source-side reference (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported):
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-task-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/task/model/AcmTask.java line 85:
            private String type;
        ArkCase's task `type` was a free-form String field on the
        AcmTask domain object (the source-side analog of this
        ServiceNow table). The field carried NO Bean Validation
        constraints (no @Size, no @NotNull, no @Pattern), so any
        caller could assign any string and the JPA / Activiti layer
        enforced no enumeration. The ServiceNow target replaces the
        free-form String with a controlled Choice vocabulary of
        four labels (Investigation, Review, Follow-up, Other)
        through the `<choice>3</choice>` setting plus the sibling
        sys_choice records. This prevents typos, enables consistent
        list-view filtering, and keeps the task-categorization
        semantics deterministic across internal forms, the Table API,
        and the seed scripts. AAP Section 0.1.2 codifies this kind
        of free-form-String -> Choice tightening as the ServiceNow-
        side equivalent of ArkCase's bean-validation enforcement.
      - The field name is `type` (lowercase, 4 chars; NOT `task_type`,
        NOT `taskType`, NOT `type_label`) per AAP Section 0.5.7
        verbatim. The intentional naming symmetry with x_casemgmt_case
        .type means cross-table reports can render a unified "Type"
        column header without per-table label aliasing, mirroring the
        same naming-symmetry rationale that established `subject` on
        both x_casemgmt_case and x_casemgmt_case_task.

    Constraints honored (AAP Sections 0.7.1, 0.7.2, 0.7.4):
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity: `<name>` resolves to
        `x_casemgmt_case_task` within the scoped application, and
        `<sys_scope>` / `<sys_package>` bind THIS dictionary record to
        the same scope by `source` attribute lookup. NO global-scope
        writes - the OOB tables `task`, `incident`, `sys_user`, etc.
        are never modified by this dictionary entry or any other
        artifact in the Update Set.
      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_ids: the `<sys_scope>` and
        `<sys_package>` text-node values resolve by scope source name
        (`x_casemgmt`), not by literal sys_id. The
        `<sys_id>` text-node value is THIS record's own deterministic
        primary key (MD5 of the canonical field identifier
        `x_casemgmt_case_task.type`) and is NOT a reference to any
        other record. The MD5 derivation guarantees that re-generation
        of this Update Set on any agent run produces a byte-identical
        `<sys_id>` (no random UUIDs), which is required for clean
        Update-Set re-import on a fresh PDI without creating duplicate
        sys_dictionary rows. The same derivation pattern is used by
        every sys_dictionary record in this Update Set (e.g.,
        x_casemgmt_case_task.subject -> 8cd658b766c404ce4445d191adabd14c,
        x_casemgmt_case_task.case   -> 25cae07ed16e95fd89a4c8013152ecc2,
        x_casemgmt_case.type        -> 9a49190f6a6b8f2b4100073c53631168).
      - The concrete scope identifier `casemgmt` is used per AAP convention;
        ServiceNow Update Set imports use a standard XML parser, so the
        scope id must be concrete in the XML before export. The identifier appears in `<name>`, `<sys_scope>`,
        `<sys_package>`, and `<sys_update_name>` consistently.
      - mandatory=false at the dictionary level per AAP Section 0.5.7
        verbatim ("type | Choice | Investigation, Review, Follow-up,
        Other" - no Mandatory marker) and AAP Section 0.7.1
        strict-literal "no additions, no renames, no type relaxations"
        rule. The AAP authoritative text takes precedence over the
        earlier functional argument that "every task has a type."
        Although the four-label vocabulary is deliberately rich enough
        to categorize any conceivable task (with "Other" serving as
        the deliberate non-empty default-of-last-resort), AAP Section
        0.5.7 does not require a dictionary-level mandatory constraint
        to enforce that classification. Internal-form callers, Table
        API consumers, and the synthetic demo tasks per
        ../seed-data/tasks/x_casemgmt_case_task_demo_*.xml continue to
        populate this field explicitly with one of the four supported
        labels at insert time. The contrast with case_task.subject
        (which IS marked Mandatory in AAP Section 0.5.7 and therefore
        carries mandatory=true in
        ../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_task_subject.xml) is intentional:
        AAP authoritative text differentiates the two fields and the
        dictionary entries reflect that exactly. If a future requirement
        makes type strictly mandatory, AAP Section 0.5.7 will be
        updated first and this dictionary entry will follow.
      - read_only=false: an internal user (case_manager or assigned
        case_agent within the AAP Section 0.5.6 "Assigned only"
        condition) editing the task record may correct an erroneous
        type assignment (e.g., a task initially classified as
        "Investigation" later proves to be a "Review" step). The
        read_only=false setting permits the write through the standard
        form, the Table API, and the seed scripts. Internal-user
        write authorization is governed by the table-level ACLs in
        ../acl/ - this dictionary entry deliberately does NOT carry
        per-role write_roles since the table-level ACLs apply
        uniformly across all editable fields on x_casemgmt_case_task.
      - default_value is EMPTY (no implicit default) per the agent
        prompt's Phase 4 verbatim ("user picks"). Defaulting silently
        to "Investigation" or "Other" would silently mask submissions
        that failed the mandatory-enforcement intent and skew any
        future "tasks by type" report. The user MUST explicitly
        choose, either through the internal form or via an explicit
        setValue() in seed scripts.
      - audit=false per AAP Section 0.3.1 minimal-change clause and
        the agent prompt's Phase 4. Task type is descriptive metadata,
        not a regulated lifecycle attribute. The additional sys_audit
        row per update would be unnecessary overhead for a POC.
      - max_length=40 per the agent prompt's Phase 3 verbatim. The
        longest defined label is "Investigation" (13 characters); the
        40-character ceiling accommodates extensible future labels
        (e.g., "Compliance Review", "External Verification") without
        a schema migration. The same 40-character ceiling is used on
        every Choice field in this Update Set (case.type, case.status,
        case.priority, case.pending_reason, case_task.status,
        case_party.party_type) for consistency.
      - choice=3 = "Choice list, no description column" per the agent
        prompt's Phase 3 verbatim. This is the standard Choice-field
        configuration when a sibling sys_choice record set defines
        the allowed values; the form renderer presents the field as
        a select dropdown sourced from the matching sys_choice rows.
        choice=0 (free-form String) would defeat the purpose of
        constraining the field to a controlled vocabulary; choice=1
        (Choice list with description) would impose a description
        column that AAP Section 0.5.7 does not specify; choice=2
        (Suggestion list) would let users input arbitrary strings
        adjacent to the suggested ones, contradicting the intent.
      - unique=false: multiple tasks with the same type are explicitly
        permitted, both within a single case (a complex case may have
        three "Investigation" tasks decomposed into sub-areas) and
        across cases (every case may have an "Investigation" task).
        Uniqueness is not a meaningful concept for a categorical
        Choice field.
      - text_index=false per the agent prompt's Phase 6 verbatim. A
        Choice field with four labels does not benefit from a text
        index; users navigate type via the Choice dropdown and
        list-view filters, not free-form full-text search.
      - spell_check=false per the agent prompt's Phase 6 verbatim.
        A controlled Choice vocabulary is by definition correctly
        spelled; spell_check on a Choice field would produce false
        positives on label tokens that the platform dictionary does
        not recognize (e.g., "Follow-up" hyphenation patterns).
      - No reference target: this is a String-backed Choice field,
        not a Reference field. All `<reference*>` elements are empty
        and `<table_reference>false</table_reference>`. The field
        does NOT reference an external lookup table; the choice
        values live as sys_choice rows keyed by element name.
      - No PII: the field stores only categorical labels chosen from
        a controlled vocabulary; no real names, email addresses,
        organizational identifiers, or any source-side ArkCase
        production data are derived from or stored in this column
        at any point in the build (per AAP Section 0.3.2 synthetic-
        data-only constraint).

    Cross-references (AAP Section 0.5.2 dependency ordering):
      - This record MUST load AFTER:
          * ../tables/x_casemgmt_case_task.xml (parent table; the
            `<name>x_casemgmt_case_task</name>` element below references
            the table by name, and the table must exist before any of
            its dictionary entries can be attached)
          * ../app/sys_app/x_casemgmt_case_management.xml and
            ../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml (scoped application records;
            <sys_scope> and <sys_package> resolve against them by source
            name)
      - This record MUST load BEFORE:
          * ../choices/sys_choice_case_task_type.xml (the choice values
            Investigation, Review, Follow-up, Other - with the literal
            "Follow-up" hyphen per AAP Section 0.5.7 verbatim - which
            reference this dictionary entry by `name` + `element` lookup
            against the strings `x_casemgmt_case_task` and `type`)
          * ../seed-data/tasks/x_casemgmt_case_task_demo_*.xml (synthetic
            demo tasks per AAP Section 0.7.4 must populate this mandatory
            field with one of the four supported labels. The seed data
            references this column by `element=type` and would fail to
            insert if this sys_dictionary record were absent)
          * ../scripts/seed_demo_data.js (the idempotent server-side seed
            script writes synthetic task type labels via
            GlideRecord.setValue('type', ...))

    Source for the deterministic sys_id derivation:
        echo -n "x_casemgmt_case_task.type" | md5sum
        => 180d00dda06c4b93e4c2c106b621d153

    The MD5 input is the canonical field identifier <name>.<element>,
    matching the same derivation pattern used across all other
    sys_dictionary records in this Update Set.

    Critical naming note carried forward to ../choices/sys_choice_case_task_type.xml:
        The third label is "Follow-up" (with literal hyphen between
        "Follow" and "up"), NOT "Follow up" (with space) and NOT
        "Followup" (with no separator). AAP Section 0.5.7 verbatim
        spells the label "Follow-up". The Update Set re-import
        gate per AAP Section 0.7.3 will detect any deviation as a
        preview error because the sys_choice rows must reference
        this dictionary entry exactly.
-->
<record_update table="sys_dictionary">
    <sys_dictionary action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
        <active>true</active>
        <array>false</array>
        <attributes/>
        <audit>false</audit>
        <calculation/>
        <choice>3</choice>
        <choice_field/>
        <choice_table/>
        <column_label>Type</column_label>
        <comments>Optional Choice categorizing the task per AAP Section 0.5.7 verbatim (no Mandatory marker). Values: Investigation, Review, Follow-up, Other. Authored as separate sys_choice rows in ../choices/sys_choice_case_task_type.xml. Surfaces in the case_task list view, the parent case's task related list, and the auto-generated form. Replaces ArkCase AcmTask.type (free-form String, no validator). Internal forms, Table API, and seed tasks all populate this field explicitly with one of the supported labels.</comments>
        <create_roles/>
        <default_value/>
        <defaultsort/>
        <delete_roles/>
        <dependent/>
        <dependent_on_field/>
        <display>true</display>
        <dynamic_creation>false</dynamic_creation>
        <dynamic_creation_script/>
        <dynamic_default_value/>
        <dynamic_ref_qual/>
        <element>type</element>
        <element_reference>false</element_reference>
        <foreign_database/>
        <function_definition/>
        <function_field>false</function_field>
        <internal_type>string</internal_type>
        <mandatory>false</mandatory>
        <max_length>40</max_length>
        <name>x_casemgmt_case_task</name>
        <next_element/>
        <primary>false</primary>
        <read_only>false</read_only>
        <read_roles/>
        <reference/>
        <reference_cascade_rule/>
        <reference_floor/>
        <reference_key/>
        <reference_qual/>
        <reference_qual_condition/>
        <reference_type/>
        <sizeclass/>
        <spell_check>false</spell_check>
        <staged>false</staged>
        <sys_class_name>sys_dictionary</sys_class_name>
        <sys_created_by>admin</sys_created_by>
        <sys_created_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_created_on>
        <sys_id>180d00dda06c4b93e4c2c106b621d153</sys_id>
        <sys_mod_count>0</sys_mod_count>
        <sys_name/>
        <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_casemgmt">x_casemgmt</sys_package>
        <sys_policy/>
        <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_casemgmt</sys_scope>
        <sys_update_name>sys_dictionary_x_casemgmt_case_task_type</sys_update_name>
        <sys_updated_by>admin</sys_updated_by>
        <sys_updated_on>2025-01-01 00:00:00</sys_updated_on>
        <table_reference>false</table_reference>
        <text_index>false</text_index>
        <unique>false</unique>
        <use_dependent_field>false</use_dependent_field>
